      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0668P0-02049'>
        <a name='S5LV0668P0_20050117_GCR_83'>  </a>
        <blockquote cite='http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-bryan-davies' class='contribution_text entry-content'>
          <a class='speech-permalink permalink' href='#S5LV0668P0_20050117_GCR_83' title='Link to this speech by Mr Bryan Davies' rel='bookmark'>&sect;</a>
          <cite class='member author entry-title'><a href="/people/mr-bryan-davies" title="Mr Bryan Davies">Lord Davies of Oldham</a></cite>
          <p class='first-para'>
            If anyone is asking me to challenge the noble Lord, Lord Tebbit, on the definition of a public nuisance, all I can say is that I do not have a 25-year record to fall back on in those terms. However, I hear what he says. The clause is in the Bill because of the obvious dangers if such impersonation is carried out. It mirrors the provision in other Acts with regard to transport inspectors. There is just cause for anxiety on the matter.
          </p>
        </blockquote>
      </div>
      
      <div class='hentry member_contribution' id='S5LV0668P0-02050'>
